jan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Calverley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): habitational name from Calverley in Yorkshire, named with Old English <i>calfra</i> (genitive plural of <i>calf</i> ‘calf’) + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. Alternatively, in some instances the name may be a variant of the habitational name <b>Calveley</b>, from a place so called in Cheshire (with the same meaning as above), or from Calverleigh in Devon, meaning ‘the clearing of the bare wood’ (Old English <i>calu</i> ‘bare, bald’ + <i>wudu</i> ‘wood’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’)."],"variants":[{"name":"Calvery","meanings":["English: shortened form of   Calverley  .","Possibly an Americanized form of German <b>Kälberer</b>(see   Kalberer  )."]},{"name":"Caverly","meanings":["English (Middlesex): shortened form of   Calverley  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Walter de Calverley was born in 1165, in Calverley, West Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Lord John de Calverley, was 45 and his mother, Lady Jennet de Luttrell, was 15. He married Lady Joan de Swillington in Swillington, Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in 1235, in his hometown, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1165–1235":"1165–1235","1162–Male":"1162–Surnud","1165–Male":"1165–Surnud","1169–Male":"1169–Surnud","1155–Female":"1155–Surnud","1180–1226":"1180–1226","1183–1301":"1183–1301","1192–Male":"1192–Surnud","1120–1205":"1120–1205","1150–1227":"1150–1227","abt 1180":"umbes 1180","1165":"1165","1120":"1120","1162":"1162","1183":"1183","1150":"1150","1192":"1192","1180":"1180","1205":"1205","1227":"1227","1226":"1226","1235":"1235","1301":"1301","1169":"1169","about 1226":"umbes 1226","1155":"1155","about 1167":"umbes 1167","1904":"1904","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Calverley, West Yorkshire, England":"Calverley, West Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Swillington, Yorkshire, England":"Swillington, Yorkshire, England","Calverley, Yorkshire, England":"Calverley, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1165–1235":"1165–1235","1162–Male":"1162–Kuollut","1165–Male":"1165–Kuollut","1169–Male":"1169–Kuollut","1155–Female":"1155–Kuollut","1180